<p><b>A/HRC/25/50/Add.3 
</b></p>
<p><b>12</b>  
</p>
<p>protect human rights as well as to investigate public maladministration.38 In this regard, the 
Ombudsman has been active on several issues, such as access to social security benefits, 
pensions and family allowances; health and education; services of public utilities, such as 
water and sanitation; environmental pollution affecting, among others, the rights to health, 
adequate housing and water and sanitation;39 and access to public transport of persons with 
disabilities.   
</p>
<p><b> C. Framework for public debt management  
</b></p>
<p>44. Under the National Constitution, the Congress40 is empowered &#8220;to borrow money on 
the credit of the Nation&#8221;41 and to settle the payment of the domestic and foreign debt of the 
country.42 It has been asserted that this requirement is fulfilled by the Congress through the 
approval of budget acts which determine annually the budget of the State, including its 
provision for debt service payments. In the Independent Expert&#8217;s view, however, article 75, 
paragraph 7, of the National Constitution provides for a more active role of Congress in 
public financial management than the mere passing of budgetary acts. 
</p>
<p>45. In the terms of article 85, the National General Auditing Office, a technical advisory 
body of the Congress, must participate in the approval or rejection of the public revenue 
and investment accounts. 
</p>
<p>46. The Fiscal Responsibility Law of 2004 sets out rules of fiscal transparency as well 
as fiscal targets for the national and provincial governments and the federal capital district. 
The procedural rules and transparency requirements include three-year budgets; that new 
borrowing or guarantees must be approved by the Ministry of Economy and Public 
Finance; that provincial governments may not issue non-peso domestic bonds; and the  
publication of fiscal accounts and all debt-related transactions. The Law further enjoins the 
national and provincial governments to put money into stabilization funds and establishes a 
federal council for fiscal responsibility, with membership from the national and all the 
provincial ministries of finance.  
</p>
<p>47. In terms of fiscal targets, the provinces have to budget primary surpluses sufficient 
to bring their debt service gradually below 15 per cent of current revenues (net of transfers 
to municipalities) and may not engage in new borrowing if their debt service exceeds the 
ceiling. The national Government has to maintain a downward trend in debt, measured in 
terms of GDP. 
</p>
<p>48. It is notable that the National Public Credit Office provides technical assistance to 
the provincial debt management offices. 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>38
 National Constitution of Argentina, art. 86; see also Act 24.284 on the Organic and Functional 
</p>
<p>Regulation of the Office of the <i>Defensor del Pueblo</i>. 
 
</p>
<p>39
 See, for example, the work of the National Ombudsman on the Mantanza-Riachuelo Basin, available 
</p>
<p>from www.dpn.gob.ar/areas.php?cl=24&amp;act=list. 
 
</p>
<p>40
 Consisting of the House of Deputies, comprising representatives directly elected by the people of 
</p>
<p>each province and the Autonomous City of Buenos Aires or the capital city, and the Senate, 
comprising three senators from each province and three from the City of Buenos Aires. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>41
 National Constitution of Argentina, art. 75(4). 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
